TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Maturity Rat Race
AU  - BRUNNERMEIER, MARKUS K.
AU  - OEHMKE, MARTIN
Y1  - 2013/04/01
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2013/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12005
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 483
EP  - 521
VL  - 68
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12005
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Why do some firms, especially financial institutions, finance themselves so short-term? We show that extreme reliance on short-term financing may be the outcome of a maturity rat race: a borrower may have an incentive to shorten the maturity of an individual creditor's debt contract because this dilutes other creditors. In response, other creditors opt for shorter maturity contracts as well. This dynamic toward short maturities is present whenever interim information is mostly about the probability of default rather than the recovery in default. For borrowers that cannot commit to a maturity structure, equilibrium financing is inefficiently short-term.
ER  - 
